{"parentUuid": null, "isSidechain": true, "promptId": "6c3a0b22-aa71-4abe-86b8-7ed7f2e35c75", "agentId": "a0a5cba3ffcbda90c", "type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": "Adversarially verify this finding about the repo at /home/jleechan/projects/ez-gh-actions (public: github.com/jleechanorg/ez-gh-actions, evidence at /home/jleechan/projects/ez-gh-actions/evidence/e2e-20260703, run https://github.com/jleechanorg/ez-gh-actions/actions/runs/28685531107). Try to REFUTE it by reading the actual code/evidence and, where relevant, live gh queries. Finding from \"code-bugs\" (major): `ezgha stop` races the serve loop and does not stop the installed service \u2014 runners resurrect within 30 seconds\nmain.rs:192-217, service.rs. `InstallService` installs a systemd --user unit with `Restart=on-failure` / launchd `KeepAlive=true` running `ezgha serve`, whose loop calls `ensure_count` every 30s forever (main.rs:201-211). `Commands::Stop` only calls `stop_all()` \u2014 it never touches the service or signals the serve process. Concrete scenario: operator installed the service, later runs `ezgha stop` during an incident (e.g. the disk is full and they want runners GONE); the command prints 'removed N managed container(s)' and exits 0, and \u226430s later the serve daemon re-registers and re-spawns everything. During an actual disk-exhaustion incident the disk-floor bail in ensure_count may prevent respawn, but for every other stop reason (security incident, runaway job, maintenance) stop is a lie. There is also no locking between a foreground `ezgha serve`/`ezgha start` and the service instance: both read `managed_containers()` then spawn the shortfall, so two concurrent processes can each see alive=0 and both spawn `count` runners (2x capacity).\nRefute if the factual basis is wrong, the scenario cannot occur, or severity is inflated (severity inflation alone -> not refuted, but say so)."}, "uuid": "e9a0b4a1-0f17-4d5b-af1d-81ee9fd8a28f", "timestamp": "2026-07-03T22:2